abstract = {Mean and median fracture transmissivities exhibit a complex trend with depth in a heavily faulted metamorphic rock environment. The general trend of decreasing transmissivities with depth can be explained by increasing overburden stress and non-linear fracture stiffness and exhibits differences between low grade and high grade metamorphic/intrusive rocks. At depth, conductive fracture transmissivities are increasingly dominated by contact metamorphic aureoles around Variscan intrusions. These cause a reversal in the transmissivity-depth trend and are caused by more brittle hornfelses in the inner contact metamorphic aureole. The extension of the hydraulically effective aureole is higher for lower grade schists and phyllites than in higher grade gneisses. The median equivalent continuum rock mass conductivity is mainly controlled by the increase of spacing of transmissive fractures rather than increasing transmissivities around intrusions and therefore is independent from contact metamorphism. With increasing depth, flow through the matrix blocks and therefore the primary (lithology dependent) porosity of the protolith becomes progressively more important},
